Observation Details: Returned today in search of the vireo for a photograph.  After 3 1/2 hours of birding in smoke from a 9000 acre forest fire, we found the bird in the grove of trees between the upper parking lot and HQ above the sidewalk.  The bird is as described by Nick Mrvelij and Peyton Cook with help from Russ Namitz on 9/2/19, the same day we saw the bird the first time. A thick bill eliminated a ruby-crowned kinglet.  Pale lores, incomplete pale eye ring separated this bird from Cassin's.  We also looked at many photos in ebird of both species and believe this is a Hutton's vireo. Awesome!

Observation Details: Superficially like a kinglet, this bird differentiated by having a thicker, bluish bill with a hooked tip, and by lacking black at the base of the secondaries (as is diagnostic with Ruby-crowned Kinglets). Additionally, the legs were rather stout and all bluish, including the toes - not black with yellowish toes as is typical with kinglets. The Hutton’s Vireo was first heard doing the typical harsh "whine" call (as named by Pieplow), which is a rising and abrupt alarm call, typically in slow series. I was able to locate the vireo on the east side of the park, in the trees near the bridge by the El Rio parking lot. A compact and large-headed vireo with overall greenish upperparts, and olive cast below. Pale crescents surrounded the eyes in front, below and behind, creating an eye-ringed look. The lores were completely pale, differentiating it from Plumbeous or Cassin's vireos. Two pale wing bars on gray-green wings with greenish flight feather edges; no black base of the secondaries, so no dark wing panel as in kinglets. The Hutton's Vireo gleaned actively while scolding its whine call repeatedly.

The bird is as described by Nick Mrvelij and Peyton Cook with help from Russ Namitz on 9/2/19, the same day we saw the bird the first time. A thick bill eliminated a ruby-crowned kinglet. Observation Details: The Hutton’s was in the early part of the nature trail.  It was in the small woods a little after the trail turns S to head towards the reed bed and lake.  Ruby-crowned Kinglets and Hutton’s Vireos are much alike.  The photo below does not provide a look at the broken eye-ring, which is similar for both species.  However, this shot does show certain markers distinctive to the Hutton’s.  They are the hooked upper mandible of the vireo, bluish gray legs & feet, and the fact the greenish edges go right up to the bottom of the secondaries.  In contrast, a Ruby-crown has a thin bill, black legs & yellowish soles of feet, and a black bar about half the distance along the base of the secondaries.

Observation Details: I think this was a life bird for me on this date. I have to mention that at least 1 bird was seen most times I walked up into the oaks in the S fork until the fall 2016. This last winter ( Nov 2016 to early Apr 2017) I never saw any.

Foraging in a mixed species flock with warblers, titmice and ruby-crowned kinglets. A first for me in this location. Slow and deliberate movements while capturing a mothlike insect allowed me to focus on this individual while it pounded its meal against branches. Unlike kinglets in the vicinity, it didn't flick wings and stayed put on limbs. No vocals. Photos illustrate the wing bars typical of a Hutton's vireo, darkest between the bars, without the dark trailing swatches of a ruby-crowned kinglet. There is a hint of visible "spectacles," a broken eye-ring, a thicker bill and the large-headed character of a Hutton's vireo.

A stocky vireo with a whitish eyering, thicker in front and back, with pale greenish lores - lacking the dark spectacle line as in the lores of Cassin’s.  Reminiscent of a kinglet, with olive-gray uppers and two white wing bars, but lacking the diagnostic black base of the secondaries. The bill was thick with a hooked tip, with a bluish upper mandible and a horn-colored lower. Legs were overall thick and bluish, typical of vireo. It was seen in the same general vicinity as the Hutton's Vireo documented on December 3, 2023 - along the wash by the bridge, near the El Rio parking lot.

First heard it doing its unique “laughing” call - a series of upslurred and jerky whinnies, non-musical, nasal and rushed. I then saw the vireo gleaning from the shrubs above the wash, about half a mile south of the parking lot. A stocky, large-headed vireo with a bold white eyering, thickest behind the eye, and broken above. Superficially similar to a Ruby-crowned Kinglet, but note the thick bluish bill with the hooked tip, and the lack of black coloration at the base of the folded secondaries. Additionally, note the sturdy, bluish legs. This is a typical individual of the “interior” stephansi subspecific group, showing the gray coloration of the head, and bolder white wing bars.

Initially I identified this species as a Ruby-crowned Kinglet but fellow birder, Steve Hosmer, correctly identified it as a Hutton's Vireo, rare for Anthem, Arizona. The thicker bill and wing bars are the differences that he pointed out. The leg coloring was obscured due to being behind tree branches. Upon recalling the moment, this bird was not as twitchy as a kinglet. I have changed the species on my list and pictures with the correct identification. The vireo was spotted on the east side of Anthem Community Park   off of the sidewall between the baseball field and natural wash facing the Anthem Community Center.  I am glad the pictures show enough details of this species which I have not encountered before. Thank you, Steve, for pointing out the features for me.

Viewed in juniper stand on the south end of the lake on the west(ish) shore where the black-crowned night herons commonly roost.  Initial ID was of a RCKI but individual gave me a strong Hutton's impression and so I photographed the individual. Photo examination (along with second opinions) confirmed ID of Hutton's.  Small plump bird, greenish/drap wash, broken eye-ring above the eye, broad pale/mottled lores and hooked bill.  The bird also had solid blue/grey legs and feet and lacked dark horizontal bar below wingbar typical of kinglets.

Initially I thought I saw a Ruby-crowned Kinglet. However, I was struck by how sluggish the bird seemed and immediately suspected Hutton's Vireo and began to study the bird closely. There is no doubt at all it was a Hutton's Vireo. The lores were obviously pale. There was a prominent white eye ring. There were two bold white wing bars. The bill was large and hooked and solid gray, absolutely not a kinglet. I would have called the legs, including the feet, gray. Field guides calls them bluish. But they weren't black and the feet weren't yellow, like a kinglet. I used a little playback just to try to confirm what I was seeing and because the bird had moved out of view. The bird was extremely responsive, coming in two separate times to five seconds of playback. He never vocalized himself, or I would have tried getting a recording. Unfortunately, I left the camera at home this morning! I did get some epically terrible shots with my phone. (The bird is mostly unidentifiable, but a couple of the pics do perhaps show the pale lores.)

Media notes: Hutton's Vireo photographed by Curtis A. Marantz on 23 November 2017 at the University of California campus, Riverside, Riverside County, California.
Observation Details: I spotted this bird foraging quietly in the lower branches of a sycamore just west of the Campus Health Center, where it remained for a few minutes before moving off.  This was a small bird with a plump body and a bill that was somewhat stouter than that of a kinglet and having a blunt tip.  I thought this bird was proportionately larger-headed than a kinglet and its eyeing was incomplete being broken above the eye and expanded behind it, two simple wingbars with a darker band between the two, but not a second band across the bases of the remiges.  The head and upperparts were olive and the underparts were a dingy olive-buff and unmarked, which combined to make this bird look much like a kinglet.  This was one of few Hutton's Vireos that I have seen in Riverside and the first that I had seen on the campus.

Observation Details: A stocky vireo with a whitish eyering, thicker in front and back, with pale greenish lores - lacking the dark spectacle line as in the lores of Cassin’s.  Reminiscent of a kinglet, with olive-gray uppers and two white wing bars, but lacking the diagnostic black base of the secondaries. The bill was thick with a hooked tip, with a bluish upper mandible and a horn-colored lower. Legs were overall thick and bluish, typical of vireo. It was seen in the same general vicinity as the Hutton's Vireo documented on December 3, 2023 - along the wash by the bridge, near the El Rio parking lot.

A compact vireo, superficially similar to Ruby-crowned Kinglet, but without the black wingbar at the base of the secondaries, which is diagnostic for kinglets. Also a thick bluish bill with a hooked tip, unlike the thin black bill of kinglets. Stout all blue-gray legs and feet - no yellowish toes and feet as it tends to be with kinglets. Told from Cassin's Vireo by compact shape, large-headed appearance (as if neck-less), and by complete eyering with greenish lores, rather than the white "spectacles" with dark-and-white loral stripes seen in vireos of the "Solitary" complex. Saw the Hutton's Vireo in the same general location as the one documented on October 31, 2023 - at the southern end of the park along the wash.

Observation Details: thanks to Russ Namitz for emailing us so quickly. This was not an easy bird in the field. Nick kept leaning towards Hutton’s so Kudos to him. Here are Nick Mrvelj’s comments: When I first saw this bird in the field, I called it a HUVI. We watched it for several minutes, taking many pictures. Due to the rarity factor, I talked myself into this being a juvenile CAVI, against my better judgement. However, even a juvenile CAVI would show a dark break in the lores, interrupting the spectacled look. This individual has pale lores, lacking this aforementioned feature. Also, the eyering is narrow near the bottom of the eye, and not continuously bold as on even a 1st fall CAVI. I’ve looked at several images of 1st fall CAVI and HUVI since this sighting, and feel this bird is a solid HUVI.

As about 5 kinglets were coming in I looked at one and saw it had bluish legs and took a double-take. It turned to face me and sure enough it had a large, hooked vireo bill and boldish spectacles like a Hutton's (not as bold as cassins thought), and otherwise matched RCKI in plumage just about exactly other than lacking the "kinglet bar" on the wing. Structurally it was different from kinglets, being larger, chunkier and just overall more plump along with having notably thicker legs (plus of course not hovergleaning). It had a weird gummed up face making it a very recognizable individual. I was shocked to REfind this bird nearly a mile away here (33.7098190, -114.4986484) 5 hours later at 2:30 pm. Photod.

Initially I thought I saw a Ruby-crowned Kinglet. However, I was struck by how sluggish the bird seemed and immediately suspected Hutton's Vireo and began to study the bird closely. There is no doubt at all it was a Hutton's Vireo. The lores were obviously pale. There was a prominent white eye ring. There were two bold white wing bars. The bill was large and hooked and solid gray, absolutely not a kinglet. I would have called the legs, including the feet, gray. Field guides calls them bluish. But they weren't black and the feet weren't yellow, like a kinglet. I used a little playback just to try to confirm what I was seeing and because the bird had moved out of view. The bird was extremely responsive, coming in two separate times to five seconds of playback. He never vocalized himself, or I would have tried getting a recording. Unfortunately, I left the camera at home this morning! I did get some epically terrible shots with my phone. (The bird is mostly unidentifiable, but a couple of the pics do perhaps show the pale lores.)

When I first saw this bird in the field, I called it a HUVI. We watched it for several minutes, taking many pictures. Due to the rarity factor, I talked myself into this being a juvenile CAVI, against my better judgement. However, even a juvenile CAVI would show a dark break in the lores (supraloral streak), interrupting the spectacled look. This individual has pale lores, lacking this aforementioned feature. Also, the eyering is narrow near the bottom of the eye, and not continuously bold as on even a 1st fall CAVI. One can also make out what appears to be an ever so slight break in the eyering above each eye. Although this feature isn’t as apparent on this individual as on the typical HY HUVI, you can still find examples of HUVI with less distinct facial features (https://youtu.be/YMzBRH_5VbY). In one of the photos, you can make out the appearance of the remnants of a fleshy gape, aging this bird as this year’s young. Judging by how fresh the remiges looked, this bird molted nearly all of its juvenile flight feathers. I’ve looked at several images of 1st fall CAVI and 1st fall HUVI since this sighting, and feel this bird is a solid 1st fall HUVI.

Observation Details: A stocky vireo with a whitish eyering, thicker in front and back, with pale greenish lores - lacking the dark spectacle line as in the lores of Cassin’s.  Reminiscent of a kinglet, with olive-gray uppers and two white wing bars, but lacking the diagnostic black base of the secondaries. The bill was thick with a hooked tip, with a bluish upper mandible and a horn-colored lower. Legs were overall thick and bluish, typical of vireo. It was seen in the same general vicinity as the Hutton's Vireo documented on December 3, 2023 - along the wash by the bridge, near the El Rio parking lot.

A compact vireo, superficially similar to Ruby-crowned Kinglet, but without the black wingbar at the base of the secondaries, which is diagnostic for kinglets. Also a thick bluish bill with a hooked tip, unlike the thin black bill of kinglets. Stout all blue-gray legs and feet - no yellowish toes and feet as it tends to be with kinglets. Told from Cassin's Vireo by compact shape, large-headed appearance (as if neck-less), and by complete eyering with greenish lores, rather than the white "spectacles" with dark-and-white loral stripes seen in vireos of the "Solitary" complex. Saw the Hutton's Vireo in the same general location as the one documented on October 31, 2023 - at the southern end of the park along the wash.

Observation Details: Holy mackerel!!! Not a bird I was ever expecting at PVER. Probably the first record for Blythe/the Colorado River part of Riverside? I presume that all LCRV records pertain to the mexican ssp though I don't really know. First seen here (33.6988281, -114.5008937) around 9:30. I heard a weird vireo call and went to investigate then got distracted by a Gray Fly coming into mob. As about 5 kinglets were coming in I looked at one and saw it had bluish legs and took a double-take. It turned to face me and sure enough it had a large, hooked vireo bill and boldish spectacles like a Hutton's (not as bold as cassins thought), and otherwise matched RCKI in plumage just about exactly other than lacking the "kinglet bar" on the wing. Structurally it was different from kinglets, being larger, chunkier and just overall more plump along with having notably thicker legs (plus of course not hovergleaning). It had a weird gummed up face making it a very recognizable individual. I was shocked to REfind this bird nearly a mile away here (33.7098190, -114.4986484) 5 hours later at 2:30 pm. Photod.

First heard it doing its unique “laughing” call - a series of upslurred and jerky whinnies, non-musical, nasal and rushed. I then saw the vireo gleaning from the shrubs above the wash, about half a mile south of the parking lot. A stocky, large-headed vireo with a bold white eyering, thickest behind the eye, and broken above. Superficially similar to a Ruby-crowned Kinglet, but note the thick bluish bill with the hooked tip, and the lack of black coloration at the base of the folded secondaries. Additionally, note the sturdy, bluish legs. This is a typical individual of the “interior” stephansi subspecific group, showing the gray coloration of the head, and bolder white wing bars.
